ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology and size of as-prepared carbon dots was evaluated by transmission electron microscopy (Fig. 2
                        ). It can been seen that carbon dots are spherical in shape. The size of the prepared dots was determined with the use of TEM image and ImageJ software: the average size of doped carbon dots is 4.939 nm (SD = 1.339). To confirm the presence of typical functional groups and the success of introducing nitrogen on the surface of the dots, an IR spectrum has been created. As can be seen in Fig. 3
                        , the absorption bands at 1538 cm−1 and 1173 cm−1 confirm that nitrogen as the doping element is immobilized at carbon dot surface. The peak at 1538 cm−1 is attributed to 1,3,5-s-tiriazine ring, and the peak at 1173 cm−1 is connected with CN bond. The elemental analysis of obtained carbon dots was conducted as well. The content of carbon, nitrogen and hydrogen were 37.71%, 38.05% and 6.85%, respectively. These results confirm that as-prepared carbon dots have high nitrogen concentration at the surface. In Iqbal et al.'s [21] work, nitrogen content was 54.98%, which was much higher than our results. However, in another study (see Table 2) in which the carbon dots doped with nitrogen were used, the results were significantly lower (e.g. 9.92% [14]) than the results of this research.

A necessary step in the synthesis of carbon dots for the determination of analytes in real samples is selection of the procedure conditions such as pH of the medium and time needed to stabilize the assay in the medium as well as the time when the quenching effect caused by mercury is the greatest. For this purpose, a set of the Britton-Robinson buffers with different pHs was prepared. Then the proper volume of as-prepared carbon dots was diluted in buffers at various pH (2−12), and the resulting fluorescence spectra were recorded. The study shows that the highest native fluorescence of the CDs was obtained when carbon dots were diluted in neutral buffer (pH = 7). Also the quenching effect was the highest at this pH (Fig. 4
                           ). Another important parameter was time when the native FL is stable and the highest in selected medium. The test demonstrated that the value of carbon dot fluorescence was constant after 25 min and that 30 min are required for the significant and highest quenching of FL by mercury(II). These experiments demonstrate that the obtained carbon dots showed excellent stability and the fluorescence of them did not change significantly at pH = 7 and after 30 min of incubation. It is also important to note that these carbon dots can be kept stable at 4 °C in the dark for more than five months (Fig. 5
                           ).

The first aspect considered during method selection was carbon dots behavior in the obtained extract of milk. Unfortunately, when ACN (1) and TCA (2) were used in protein precipitation, the value of native fluorescence was not stable (Fig. 7B). As the authors' research had shown that the best medium for the synthesized carbon dots is the medium with pH = 7 and the extracts after protein precipitation had an acidic pH, an attempt was made to equalize the pH with NaOH solution. Yet despite the fact that the pH was neutral, the carbon dots fluorescence in the extracts was still unstable (SD > 87) and the obtained results would have been affected by a large error. It was thus necessary to apply a method that would effectively remove proteins from milk while not introducing a precipitant that would disturb the work of carbon dots. For this purpose, an Amicon filter tube with 3 kDa was used, which provided an easy way to obtain clean and transparent milk extract. An appropriate volume of milk was transferred into an Amicon tube and after centrifuging, the clean extract was used for further analysis. This fast method produced a matrix in which the fluorescence of the assay was stable (SD < 3). This made it possible to prepare solutions containing the human milk matrix and to examine the CDs behavior at different concentrations (2.81–51.05 μM) of heavy metals such as mercury(II), taking into account the matrix effect (Fig. 8
                        ). As presented in Table 3
                        , a good recovery (determined for milk spiked with 2.81, 3.67, and 4.78 μM mercury (II) solution) was obtained in the range of 74–111%. These data suggest that this kind of assay has potential in practical applications.
